File S8: Sequencing depth across GC values

Eric S. Tvedte

November 4, 2019

Usage

Sequencing depth was determined across GC values for Riptide and non-Riptide Illumina libraries.

Unix commands are given in blue.

Input dataset

This analysis requires reference genome FASTA files in addition to BAM files of primary reads mapped to corresponding genomes.

1. Make genomebed file

awk -v OFS= {print $1, $2} genome.fasta.fai > genomefile.bed

2. Make overlapping sliding window intervals

bedtools makewindows -g /genomefile.bed -w 1000 -s 500 > genome_windows_ovl.bed

3. Determine GC content of sliding windows

bedtools nuc -fi genome.fasta -bed genome_windows_ovl.bed | awk {print $1,$2, $3, $5} - | tail -n +2 - > GC.txt

4. Determine mode depth for each sliding window

bedtools coverage -sorted -d -a $WINDOWSBED -b $BAM | sort -k1,1 -k2,2n | groupBy -g 1,2,3 -c 5 -o mode | awk {print $4} - > mode.txt

5. Organize output files

paste GC.txt mode.txt > data.txt

echo -e scaffold_start_end_content_depth" > header.txt

cat header.txt data.txt | sed -e s/ //g > depth+GCstats.txt

library(ggplot2)
## Warning: package 'ggplot2' was built under R version 3.5.3

Acinetobacter

#Riptide
rip.path = "Y:/RDRIP/etvedte/GC_Content/BEDtools_w1000s500/RDRIP_20180711_K00134_IL100105221_GCCGTTAA-Abaumannii_L007_depth+GCstats.txt"
data <- read.table(rip.path, header = T, sep = '\t')
data$GC_content <- data$GC_content * 100
GC.data <- data[ which(data$GC_content >= 20 & data$GC_content <= 60), ]

GC.data$GC_content <- round(GC.data$GC_content, digits = 0)

#pdf open
#pdf("Y:/RDRIP/etvedte/GC_Content/BEDtools_w1000s500/Acinetobacter_Riptide_GCvsdepth.pdf", width = 6.5, height = 1.75)

  bp <- ggplot(GC.data, aes(x=factor(GC_content), y=log10(mode_depth + 1))) + 
        labs(x="window GC content (%)",y="log10(mode depth of coverage + 1)") +
        geom_boxplot(fill=c('#e6194b'), outlier.size = 0.5) +
        ggtitle("Acinetobacter - Riptide") + 
        theme_bw()
        
  bp 

#pdf close
